m/api/questions/16095/relationships/activeRevision"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"packs":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/packs","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/packs"}},"revisions":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/revisions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/revisions"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16095"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/content"}},"specialtyTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/specialtyTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/specialtyTags"}},"primaryTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/primaryTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/primaryTags"}},"contributionTypes":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/contributionTypes","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/contributionTypes"}},"contributors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/contributors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/contributors"}},"contribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/contribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/contribution"}},"myContribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/myContribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/myContribution"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49342"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/activeRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/activeRevision"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3949"},{"type":"tags","id":"3953"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"53219"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8786/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following an assault where he was stabbed in the back with a knife. He develops progressive weakness of his right leg and altered sensation in both legs. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a full-time university student.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears stable with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals right-sided weakness below T8, loss of proprioception and vibration sense on the right side, and reduced pain and temperature sensation on the left side below the level of injury. He requires assistance with all mobility at present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of the spine confirms a right-sided penetrating injury at T8 with cord signal change consistent with Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely rehabilitation outcome at six months?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bed-bound requiring full nursing care","Dependent on wheelchair for mobility","Minimal motor or sensory recovery","Independent ambulation with or without aids","Independent ambulation with some assistance"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient clinical signs point to Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome, which is characterised by a hemisection of the spinal cord resulting in ipsilateral weakness and proprioception sensory loss with contralateral pain and temperature loss below the level of injury. The diagnosis is confirmed by MRI showing cord signal change at T8.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndependent ambulation with or without aids\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely outcome at six months. Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome has the best prognosis among incomplete spinal cord injury patterns, with vast majority of patients achieving independent ambulation within six months. The preservation of some spinal cord pathways and the unilateral nature of the injury contribute to this favorable outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDependent on wheelchair\u003C/strong\u003E for mobility is unlikely given the typically good prognosis. While patients may initially require wheelchair use during early rehabilitation, most progress to walking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBed-bound requiring full nursing care\u003C/strong\u003E would be an extremely poor outcome and is not consistent with the natural history of Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome, which typically shows good functional recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndependent ambulation with some assistance\u003C/strong\u003E underestimates the likely degree of recovery. Most patients achieve independence in mobility by six months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMinimal motor or sensory recovery\u003C/strong\u003E would be highly unusual. The majority of patients show significant neurological improvement, particularly in motor function, within the first six months after injury. This good prognosis is thought to be due to the unilateral nature of the lesion and preservation of some ascending and descending tracts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome is characterized by ipsilateral motor weakness and proprioception loss with contralateral pain and temperature loss below the level of injury","Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome generally has a favorable prognosis compared to other incomplete spinal cord injury patterns","Recovery of independent ambulation is achieved in most patients with Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome"],"references":["Moskowitz E, Schroeppel T. Brown-sequard syndrome. Trauma Surgery \u0026 Acute Care Open. 2018 Feb 1;3(1):e000169. Available online at ; https://tsaco.bmj.com/content/tsaco/3/1/e000169.full.pdf","Little JW, Halar E. Temporal course of motor recovery after Brown-Sequard spinal cord injuries. Paraplegia. 1985 Feb;23(1):39-46. doi: 10.1038/sc.1985.7. PMID: 3982846. Available online at ; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3982846/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49342"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16095"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63912/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T19:12:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T19:13:10+10:30"},"relationsh